"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Landen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Swedish (<b>Landén</b>): ornamental name composed of the element <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-én</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Landin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Landin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Carlos, Jose, Juan, Alicia, Lupe, Angel, Araceli, Criselda, Evaristo, Francisco, Herlinda.","Spanish (mainly Galicia; <b>Landín</b>): habitational name from Landín in A Corunña province. The placename derives from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Nandinus</i>.","Swedish: ornamental name composed of the element <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Landeen   and   Landen  ."]}]},{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henri de Landen was bor